text: I actually am Emma Stone's character mix in real life, 1/4 Chinese, just more white and a little less Hawaiian. I look nothing like her-brown eyes, brown hair, tan skin. It's not just that they cast her as the main character, but also everyone else in the movie seems to be white. The huge concern here is the lack of respect and disregard for an entire people group. How dare they misrepresent Hawaii and my heritage by talking about "island spirits" and twisting the sacredness of "aloha." It's sickening rhetoric, that reinforces the "mystical exotic" vacation destination of Hawai'i.  This was once a sovereign nation of people, who had their culture decimated and stolen by a group of white businessmen, backed by the US government. After locking the Queen of Hawaii in her bedroom 200 hundred years ago and forcing her to sign over Hawaii to the USA, or pick the genocide of the Hawaiian people- because they threatened to kill everyone if she didn't sign, a movie like this gets made? I can't imagine a worse way to disrespect a whole culture. How could they NOT realize this would be upsetting?  It's the same story again, but this time they are charging people.

text: Saw the movie the other day and couldn't believe the racist. tribalist, anti-USA undertones of the entire movie. The pandering to a Hawaiian tribal king who lives in a trailer and wears a shirt that says "Hawaiian By Birth" on the front and "American By Force" on the back. The consistent insistence by co-star Emma Stone that she is "1/4" Hawaiian, the slavish and continuous referral to island myth as well as an anti-science/technology theme running through the entire film. Might as well have done the movie on an Indian reservation - it would have been much cheaper. Hawaii is a US STATE!¬† You want to experience racism as a white person? Go to Hawaii. The very idea that someone is entitled to something as an accident of birth (like the native Hawaiians are portrayed in this movie) should be repulsive to any American (any human being, frankly) - but I see no complaints anywhere - except that Cameron Crowe was "forced" to apologize for having the Emma Stone character claim 1/4 Hawaiian blood. This is sickening.
